name: 'Latin London' Walking Tours
description:
This tour allows participants to experience the city via its Early Modern Latin monuments, inscriptions and poetry, made accessible via modern translations. (c.1500-1700).
It runs from Tower of London to St Paul's Cathedral (c. 2.5 hours).
address: Traitors' Gate, Tower of London, EC3N 4DR

name: 1 Halliwick Road
description: A low energy refurbishment of an Edwardian house, with rear extension and loft conversion. Wood fibre insulation, MVHR, airtightness layer, triple glazing, timber structure and low embodied energy materials.

name: 10 Downing Street
description: 10 Downing Street has been the residence of British Prime Ministers since 1735. Behind its famous black door the most important decisions affecting Britain for the last 284 years have been taken.

name: 137 A Evering Road
description: The building is a set of four flats. Ours is Flat A in the basement. It has a unique interior and a long narrow garden.

name: 15 and a half Consort Road
description: As per Grand Designs, the opening roof, the retracting loo and sliding bed-bath typify this extraordinary response to constraints of a tight budget on a brownfield site. Shortlisted RIBA Awards 2006. One of nation's favourite TV houses.
address: 15 and a half Consort Road, SE15 2PH

name: 195 Mare Street
description: 195 Mare Street

name: 198 Contemporary Arts and Learning
description: We will be offering tours of this RIBA and AJ Retrofit award winning building. The architect will be on hand to discuss the design and construction process. We will also run  curator led tours of  the exhibition in our gallery spaces. This project is supported by the Mayor of London.
address: 198 Contemporary Arts and Learning, 198 Railton Road, SE24 0JT

name: 215 Mare Street
description: Morris+Company moved to Hackney in September 2022, a year in occupation and in collaboration with the 215 Mare St residents, it will open doors to the community and the wider public, featuring exhibitions, workshops and tours of the studios

name: 28 Lawrence Road, N15 4EG
description: The building serves as a live-and-work site for creatives, as well as our organisation, which plays an important role in the local community's life. We have two offices here, along with our Community Hub, which was designed by studio Unit38

name: 3 Arbuthnot Road
description: Open day / weekend of a contemporary house extension within a conservation area. The build was completed in 2022.

name: 6 Moretown (Gensler London Studio)
description: A contemporary adaptation of a 1980s office building, and home of global design firm Gensler. Each level of the building is connected by a structural timber facade and set of stairs, and the new 5th floor cantilevers from the roof.

name: 60 Blenheim Grove
description: Tour of custom build house at 60 Blenheim Grove

name: 75 Wallis Road
description: A characterful factory, used for the manufacture of the first manmade plastic, was given a new future as an exemplary 21st century workplace for HTA Design. Our designers will lead tours explaining our renovation decisions and challenges.

name: 8 Stoneleigh Terrace (Highgate New Town, Stage 1)
description: Built during the golden era of Camden public housing under Borough Architect Sydney Cook. Peter Tábori  studied with Ernő Goldfinger and worked with Denys Lasdun, and met Ken Adie when both were students at the Regent Street Polytechnic.

name: 8-10 Moorgate
description: Dutch bank ING moved its UK office to this special building in 2016.  The building blends a historic exterior (including its original Portland stone façade) with a modern 135,220 sqft of office space. City Heritage Award winner 2015.

name: A House for Artists
description: A House for Artists is an ambitious project, designed to provide affordable, sustainable housing for artists, who will offer long-term civic and cultural engagement for communities in Barking Town Centre. Drop in to the creative workshop. This project is supported by the Mayor of London.

name: A Ruskinian Walk Through Shared Heritage
description: Ruskinian walk from RIBA award-winning Chiswick Business Park, Gunnersbury Triangle Nature Reserve through South Acton Estate, birthplace of artist Patrick Caulfield; Woodlands Park Ice House; to home of Wm Willett, of Daylight Saving Time
address: Building 3, Chiswick Business Park, 566 Chiswick High Road, W4 5YA

name: A tour of Victorian Bromley
description: Starting at the Exhibition 'Historic Bromley Town' taking place on the Lower Mall of The Glades, the tour tells the story of Bromley's phenomenal growth in the late 19thC  showing how the town progressed from a rural market town to suburb in about 20 yrs.
address: East St, North St, High Street, Bromley, BR1 1NN

name: A1 The Institute of Creativity & Technology: Design District
description: The Institute of Creativity and Technology is based in Design District building A1, designed by Barozzi Veiga. It is a future-focused home of experimentation, connection and collaboration. Explore the building and take part in workshops.

name: A3: Design District
description: Building A3 by Adam Khan Architects with its sturdy, geometric concrete exterior, can be seen as a nod to the aesthetics of raw construction found on emerging sites across the evolving Greenwich Peninsula.
address: Building A3 Design District, Soames Walk, SE10 0BJ

name: A4 & B4: Design District
description: A pair of affordable studio buildings as part of a new creative district on the Greenwich peninsula. David Kohn Architects worked with developer Knight Dragon on two new build creative studio buildings as part of the Design District.
address: The Gateway Pavilions, Peninsula Square, SE10 0QE

name: Abbey Mills Pumping Station
description:
Abbey Mills pumping station 'A', built by engineer Joseph Bazalgette, Edmund Cooper and architect Charles Driver. Built between 1865 and 1868 it is described as the cathedral of sewage.
Follow this link to book: https://bit.ly/abbeymills

name: Aberfeldy Village
description: Aberfeldy is an ambitious regeneration project in Poplar, designed for and alongside its residents and the local community.

name: Acland Burghley School
description: An important example of 1960s comprehensive school design in the Brutalist style. Acland Burghley has recently received support from the National Lottery Heritage Fund for its ambitious ‘A Hall for All’ project and have welcomed in a resident orchestra, the Orchestra of the Age of Enlightenment in a collaborative partnership which is a UK-first.

name: Adobe Village Hounslow Heath Infant and Nursery School
description: A unique striking playscape and adobe home structure that integrates outside learning with innovative earth forms. Construction is 'rammed' earth made from earth filled tubes. Adobe construction is recognised for sound reducing properties.

name: Aga Khan Centre
description: The Aga Khan Centre, designed by Pritzker prize winning architect Fumihiko Maki, houses the UK institutions of the Aga Khan Development Network. A unique feature are its six gardens inspired by different regions of the Muslim world.
address: Aga Khan Centre, 10 Handyside Street, N1C 4DN

name: All Saints Church
description:
Historical connections
Admiral Fitzroy sailed to Galapagos Islands with Charles Darwin.
Grave within Church grounds.
Famous artist Camille Pissarro painted local scenes one of All Saints Church.
address: All Saints Church, Church Road, SE19 3EP

name: All Saints Church, Edmonton
description: Church dating back to at least early C12. Charles and Mary Lamb are buried in the churchyard.
address: All Saints Church, Church Street, N9 9AT

name: All along the dock edge
description: A walking tour, enlivened by unique illustrations, along the northern edge of Royal Albert Dock. Historically a frontier of trade into and out of London, it has had a fascinating journey from busy port to a place for people to call home.
address: In front of the Hilton Double Tree hotel Royal Albert Dock

name: Alton Estate
description: Alton Estate is renowned for its mix of high-rise Le Corbusian architecture in Alton West & its low-rise Scandinavian approach to modernism in Alton East. Designed by the London County Council  architects they completed in 1959.

name: Ancient Livery Companies in the City of London
description:
On this walk we shall discover some of the livery companies, learn about their ancient traditions and ceremonies, which are repeated every year. Also hear about  their important role in the City.
Free walks led by City of London Guides

name: Anise Gallery- The Old Chapel
description: Located inside a fully renovated 1800s Zionist Chapel in Forest Hill, Anise Gallery will be open to the public to admire and see our completed space at The Old Chapel. There will be kids arts workshops, an exhibition and artwork sale.

name: Apartment Block, 11 Kingsway Place
description: Apartment Block’ is an impeccably hand-crafted, two-storey apartment, designed by Coffey Architects as a solid piece of joinery ‘inserted’ into a Grade II listed building.

name: Architects’ Houses of Hampstead Walking Tour
description: The walk examines the homes created by architects and designers for themselves through six remarkable case studies, spanning from the 1930s to the 1970s, from the Modernist International style to the ground-breaking Hi-tech movement.

name: Argentine Ambassador's Residence
description: During the Open House Festival people will have the unique opportunity to visit and explore the historic mansion and enjoy live performance throughout the day.

name: Art Hub Open Studios
description: Art Hub Studios will be holding studio tours as part of its Open Studios event, explaining the history of the Industrial Estate, its position within the Thames Barrier & Bowater Road Conservation Area and its current use as art studios.
address: Building 28, 34 Bowater Road, Westminster Industrial Estate, SE18 5TF

name: BAPS Shri Swaminarayan Mandir
description: Europe’s first traditional Hindu temple is a masterpiece of exquisite Indian craftsmanship. Using 5,000 tonnes of Italian and Indian marble and the finest Bulgarian limestone, it was hand-carved in India before being assembled in London.

name: Baitul Futuh Mosque
description: Guided tours of the largest purpose-built mosque in Western Europe accommodating 13,000 worshippers blending of Islamic and modern British architecture. Recent developments, involving reconstruction after a fire, are nearing completion.
address: Ahmadiyya Muslim Association, 181 London Road, Morden, SM4 5PT

name: Bank of England Museum
description: The museum is part of the Bank of England rebuilding in the 1930's by Sir Herbert Baker. One room is a reconstruction of 1793 Bank of England Stock Office by Sir John Soane.

name: Barking & Dagenham - regeneration trail
description: Barking and Dagenham has become the blueprint for urban regeneration. Starting at Industria, - the UK’s first multi-storey light industrial development - and finishing at A House for Artists, this self-guided trail gives visitors the opportunity to experience the transformation of the borough. These projects are supported by the Mayor of London.

name: Barking Riverside London
description: A new sustainable neighbourhood being created alongside 2km of south-facing Thames river frontage. A partnership with The Mayor of London and L&Q, 10,800 new homes will house up to 29,000 people.
address: Barking Riverside Project Office, Project Road, Barking, IG11 0YP

name: Barking Town Centre Tour
description: Barking town centre has seen significant development over recent years with substantial growth in housing and infrastructure. These guided tours will visit existing award winning schemes and set out the vision for the future of the town.

name: Beck Road Studios: Open Studios Exhibitions
description: Explore a vibrant artist community beneath a railway arch at our open studios! Engage with talented artists, discover diverse exhibitions. Join us in celebrating the creativity and sense of togetherness that define this unique space.

name: Bells and Belfries at St Botolph Aldgate
description:
Opportunity to hear a description and watch a demonstration of bell ringing (on Saturday only).
Church built by architect of Mansion House and contains London's oldest organ.
address: St Botolph's Church, Aldgate High Street, EC3N 1AB

name: Benjamin Franklin House
description: Grade I listed Georgian house, the only surviving home of Benjamin Franklin, retaining many original features including central staircase, lathing, 18th Century panelling, stoves, windows, fittings and beams.

name: Bernie Grant Arts Centre
description: Bernie Grant Arts Centre (BGAC) is a multi-art form venue, situated in the heart of Tottenham.  As London’s only Black-led combined arts venue that prioritises Black creativity, we fulfil a critically important role in our area.

name: Bethlem Gallery clay workshops
description: These workshops give participants the opportunity to model in air-dry clay one or more structure/s on the Bethlem Royal Hospital site, then either add it to an existing display at Bethlem Gallery, or take it home, as they prefer.
address: Bethlem Gallery, Monks Orchard Road, Beckenham, BR3 3BX

name: Bethlem Royal Hospital
description: Guided walking tours of the grounds of Bethlem Royal Hospital, taking in the Hospital's historic Chapel, its beautiful grounds, Bethlem Museum of the Mind, and Bethlem Gallery. Open House 2023 tours delivered as part of This is Croydon, London Borough of Culture, with the support of Mayor of London and Croydon Council.
address: Bethlem Museum of the Mind, Beckenham, BR3 3BX

name: Bevin Court
description: One of London's hidden Modernist gems. Lubetkin's motto 'Nothing is too good for ordinary people' resonates through this building.

name: Bikeworks
description: As part of Open House 2023, Bikeworks would like to invite the public to visit to their new inclusive cycling centre of excellence and accredited training centre located opposite the Velodrome on the the Olympic Park in Stratford.

name: Billingsgate Roman House & Baths
description: Some of London's best Roman remains, comprising late 2C house with a 3C bath house built within its courtyard. First discovered in 1848.

name: Black & White Building
description: Architect led tours

name: Black Kite Studios
description: Black Kite is an award-winning independent visual effects and design studio. Their new London studio - a riot of colour and geometry by Bureau de Change - supports a collective of creatives, offering a home from home.

name: Blenheim Grove
description: The first custom-build homes built in London. A terrace of flats and houses which was built from scratch and sold at 'shell' for the owners to fit-out themselves.

name: Bloqs
description: Bloqs is the UK's first open-access factory providing flexible and affordable access to industrial machinery, workshops and training with cafe / exhibition space and events venue. Winner of 3 architectural awards in 2023 from RIBA and AJ. This project is supported by the Mayor of London.

name: Boston Manor House
description: Boston Manor House is a Jacobean House built for Lady Mary Reade in 1623 and later owned by the Clitherow family from the 1670s until the 1920s.  The House is now open to the public with free entry six days a week. Its beautifully restored historic interiors, including breath-taking original ornate plasterwork, are joined by two community exhibition galleries, meeting rooms and an attractive modern café
address: Boston Manor House, Boston Manor Road, Brentford, TW8 9JX

name: Bower House
description: Grade I listed country house commanding the most extensive southerly views over Essex. Staircase mural by Sir James Thornhill, a painter notable for the 'Painted Hall' at the Royal Naval Hospital at Greenwich. Set in grounds with a pond.
address: Orange Tree Hill, Havering-atte-Bower, Romford, RM4 1PB

name: Brady Arts and Community Centre
description: The Brady Arts & Community Centre is on Hanbury St, just off Brick Lane in the busy & creative part of East London. It opened in 1935 as the Brady Jewish Girls & Boys Clubs.  We are holding our open day on Saturday 16 September.  Come and find out about the centre’s history and take part in drop in arts activities’.

name: Bridget Riley studios
description: See behind the scenes of working studios that are not usually open to the public. Discover work by some of the UK’s top artists, from internationally acclaimed names to new and emerging talent.

name: Britannia Works studios
description: See behind the scenes of working studios that are not usually open to the public. Discover work by some of the UK’s top artists, from internationally acclaimed names to new and emerging talent.

name: Brockley's Historic Mews
description: Guided walks through Brockley Conservation Area's quirky mews: leafy lanes, industrial units, Victorian and interesting modern architecture existing in harmony. The cherished public right of way  allows community contact with nature.
address: Ashby, Wickham, Breakspears Mews, Junctions with Ashby Road, SE4 1TF

name: Bromley Archives- Bromley Central Library
description: Take a tour around Bromley Archives. The archive store itself is normally closed to the public and visitors will be allowed access within this space and a look at some of the items that we have in our collection.
address: Bromley Historic Collections, Bromley Central Library, High Street

name: Bromley and Sheppard's College
description: Founded to house the widows of clergymen, the original building consisted of 20 houses built around a classically-styled quadrangle. Captain Richard Ryder – one of Sir Christopher Wren's surveyors – was in charge of design and construction.
address: London Road (entrance via Wren Gates, no vehicle entry), Bromley

name: Bruce Castle Museum
description: Tudor Manor House built for Sir William Compton in 1514, substantially altered in 17C, 18C & 19C. A museum since 1906 housing local history and community collections, archives, art & exhibitions of Bruce Castle, and Haringey area.
address: Bruce Castle Museum,, Lordship Lane, Tottenham, N17 8NU

name: Bruce Grove Public Conveniences
description: Guided tours of Grade-II listed Public Conveniences under refurbishment to become a new social value commercial space, including the basement (c1910), ground floor pavilion (c1922) and extension (under construction) and discuss the site’s history and future.

name: Burgundy Lanes
description: The project transforms a nondescript mid-century house on Green Lanes in North London into a unique family home that is simple and restrained from the outside but sophisticated and materially rich and inside.

name: Burlington House: Linnean Society of London
description: The world's oldest active biological society. Founded in 1788, the Society takes its name from the Swedish naturalist Carl Linnaeus whose botanical, zoological and library collections have been in its keeping since 1829.

name: Burlington House: Royal Academy of Arts
description: Discover a new side of the Royal Academy of Arts, including hidden spaces not usually open to the public.

name: Burlington House: Royal Astronomical Society
description: The home of the Royal Astronomical Society since 1874, refurbished in 2007. Part of the extension to Burlington House to provide accommodation for learned societies.

name: Burlington House: Royal Society of Chemistry
description: Experience the history, architecture and science of the East Wing of Burlington House, home to the Royal Society of Chemistry. Part of the quadrangle extension to Burlington House, it was purpose built for the learned society.

name: Burlington House: The Geological Society of London
description: Home to the oldest geological society in the world, founded in 1807. The Society has been based at Burlington House since 1874, and now has over 12,000 members worldwide.

name: C2 Clod Ensemble Studios : Design District
description: The building, designed by Mole Architects, comprises a 2000 square foot rehearsal top-lit studio, open-plan office, music production studio. Constructed entirely from timber, clad in weathered steel and designed to limit energy consumption.
address: C2 Cripps Yard, Soames Walk, Design District, SE10 0BQ

name: C3 : Bureau Design at District
description: C3 is home to Bureau, a members club at the heart of Design District. Its undulating white facade creates informal pockets of space on the interior, ideal for flexible working models.

name: Cannizaro Studios
description:
Victorian Potting sheds converted to artists' studios set within the grounds of Grade II listed Cannizaro Park.
The eight resident artists will be displaying their work during the festival at these unique studios.
address: The Old Potting Sheds, Cannizaro Park, SW19 4UW

name: Carpenters' Hall
description: Livery Hall first built in 1429, much altered then demolished and rebuilt in 1880, destroyed in 1941 except for external walls (W W Pocock). Designed as a showpiece for the craft of carpentry, the third Hall on the site.

name: Central Park, War Memorial and Cafe
description: The park opened in 1898. 7,000 attended the event, enjoying refreshments and speeches stressing the importance of creating resources for children. The walkways, fountain, bowling green, war memorial and cafe were incorporated over time.

name: Chancery House
description: Chancery House, on Chancery Lane, close to Lincoln’s Inn Fields, is a building with a fascinating history. Architects DMFK redeveloped the existing building for clients The Office Group, transformed the site into a new flexible workspace.

name: Chart Street Studios
description: The redevelopment of a former furniture warehouse in Hackney. Using CLT and glulam, the existing building has been extended to include a new building over the yard as well as a new office space on the top floor of the main building.

name: Chelsea Creek: photography walk & talk
description: Join Chris Hopkinson, of Chromaphotography for an architecture photography walk around Chelsea Creek, a new canalside neighbourhood by St George. Chris is a qualified Architect, turned professional photographer & videographer.

name: Chris Dyson Architects LLP
description: Built originally as a pub (the Queen’s Head) circa 1825, at the time of parliament’s ‘road improvement scheme’, CDA’s 2016/17 renovations and extension of the building included restoration of the exterior brickwork, tiling and windows.

name: Christ Church
description: Grade II* listed church with ragstone tower, spire, good stained glass by Kempe and recently restored William Hill organ. A characteristic work of Scott. It is Gothic Revival in the style of the 13C.

name: Christ Church Southgate and the Minchenden Oak Garden
description: Grade II listed church with fine collection of Pre-Raphaelite stained glass windows by Morris & Co. including Burne Jones and Rossetti. Wall paintings. Mosaic reredos. Minchenden Oak  - ancient pollarded oak more than 800 years old.

name: Church of St Andrew the Apostle, Catford
description: St Andrew's is a Grade II* listed building by Philip Appleby Robson (1871–1951). It boasts a magnificent Arts and Crafts interior with rich wood carvings in the chancel and magnificent stained-glass windows by Martin Travers (1886–1948).

name: Church of the Annunciation
description: Fine Victorian church with large mosaic and painted reredos, screen and wall paintings and some unusual glass. Arts and crafts decoration by Nathaniel Westlake and Salviati Bros.

name: Churchill Theatre
description: Wonderful example of a repertory theatre in style of European opera houses, with vast stage, sub-stage workshops and auditorium seating 785.

name: City Information Centre
description: London's main tourist information centre is clad in a specially manufactured system of 220 pre-finished stainless steel panels. The subtly reflective surface provides a striking counterpoint to St Paul's.

name: Colour Casing
description: Awarded best project under £100k by Don’t Move Improve, Colour Casing creates the flexibility of a house within the footprint of an original small flat with a new rear and side addition.

name: Conway Hall
description: The home of Conway Hall Ethical Society, an organisation renowned as a hub for free speech and progressive thought. Grade II listed building with both Arts and Crafts and Art Deco features adding to its distinctive style.

name: Coopers' Hall
description: Coopers' Hall is a late 17th century, timber-framed merchant's house with a Georgian frontage. A Livery Hall since 1957, it features a fine Courtoom, dining room and an impressive staircase spiralling up the entire height of the building.
address: 13 Devonshire Square, City of London, EC2M 4TH

name: Crawley Road Studios
description: Crawley Road Open Studios, Tottenham Boutique and Makers Market and Turning Earth Ceramics Market, gourmet street food led by resident chefs Bolland and Crust, art exhibition and a wide range of making demonstrations and family activities.
address: Crawley Road Studios, 38 Crawley Road, N22 6QS

name: Croydon Town Hall
description: Croydon Town Hall will be opened for a limited number of guided tours, providing rare access this unique Victorian-style, Grade II listed building. Croydon Town Hall was designed by local architect Charles Henman and opened in 1896.

name: Crystal Palace Park Dinosaurs  – a tour with a London Blue Badge Tourist Guide
description:
Explore the world's first dinosaur models hidden in a south London park. The 30 Grade I listed, life-size statues of dinosaurs and other extinct animals at Crystal Palace Park have thrilled
visitors for 166 years. Tour is kids friendly.
address: Crystal Palace Overground station, Crystal Palace Overground station

name: Cut Glass Studio Ltd, Tottenham Hale
description: Unit used as an art studio in a small industrial estate.
address: 15-16 The High Cross Centre, Fountayne Road, N15 4QN

name: Cycle tour of Thamesmead
description: As a modernist 1960s development designed around extensive waterways and pedestrian routes, Thamesmead is also a perfect place for cycling. This cycle tour will take you deep into the 'Town of the 21st Century'. Highlights also include Grade I-listed Crossness Pumping Station and Lesnes Abbey ruins.
address: Outside Abbey Arms pub, (next to Abbey Wood Station, 31 Wilton Road

name: D1 & C1: Bureau at Design District
description: Building D1, designed by Architecture 00 forms one of two buildings that house Bureau, which offers coworking in the heart of Design District. D1 is home to a variety of workspaces and businesses with meeting rooms, studios and Forum.

name: D2 : Design District
description:
Building D2 designed by Mole Architects has a striking exterior with an iridescent painted finish that changes colour with the light. Internally timber was chosen for its renewable low-carbon properties.
Mole Architects also designed the adjacent C2, Ziggurat-shaped and clad in CorTen weathered steel, which makes a striking statement. The building is fitted out with a test kitchen and studios.

name: D4 : Design District
description:
D4 overlooks central square with a tall and slim facade acting as a landmark feature within
the district.
address: Building D4, Design District, Dormer Yard, 5-6 Soames Walk, SE10 0AX

name: DEEP SPACE
description: New build live/ work unit, unique architecture in a quiet mews in Brockley.

name: Dalston C.L.R. James Library & Hackney Archives
description: 4-storey multi-purpose, state of the art library and archives building.

name: Dalston Eastern Curve Garden
description: A vital community garden offering a model for maximum good for communities and for the environment on a small urban plot. It is now a site of Local Importance for Nature Conservation. Shortlisted for the Open City Stewardship Awards 2021.

name: Dawson's Heights
description: Celebrating it's 50th year this year Dawson's Heights is split between 2 blocks consisting of 296 flats, all with private balconies. A fantastic example of beautifully designed social housing with uninterrupted views of the London skyline.
address: Bredinghurst, Overhill Road, East Dulwich, SE22 0PL

name: Decolonising Wembley
description: Imperial Nostalgia & the Built Environment –  A thought-provoking keynote address followed by a panel discussion exploring the theme of imperial nostalgia in the built environment, using Wembley as a case study.

name: Deep Retrofit to 1960's terrace house
description: This house is a deep low carbon retrofit to classic late twentieth century terrace house typology by the owner architect. Alongside energy demand reduction to EnerPHit criteria and comfort improvement, the house interior has been remodelled

name: Deep Retrofit to a Detached 1960s House
description: One of several houses that have had a whole house deep retrofit. Energy efficiency measures include significant  insulation (external, internal, floor, cavity and loft), air tightness measures, triple glazed windows, MVHR, and ASHP.

name: Deptford Nurseries Walking Tour
description: This tour will tell the story of the English nursery - bringing milk, sunshine and playtime to slum children, giving working women a safe place to send their infants, taking over spaces that were designed for other things.

name: Design District Canteen
description: Designed by SelgasCano, listen to musicians perform in different areas inside and outside of Canteen during the festival. We'll be showcasing some of London's best independent musicians. Enjoy food and drink from global street food traders.

name: Design District Public Realm
description: Design District is a collection of 16 buildings designed by eight architects, one minute from North Greenwich station. The District supports an ecosystem of creative businesses and helps foster connections through affordable spaces, comprehensive facilities and a thriving events programme.
address: The Gateway Pavilions, Peninsula Square, SE10 0QE

name: Devonport Mausoleum
description: Beautiful mausoleum in former Royal Navy cemetery, restored 1999 by the University of Greenwich. Many interesting plaques and grave stones.

name: Dr Johnson's House
description: Fine example of an early 5-floor Queen Anne town house with original panelling, open staircase and unique 'swinging panels' on the open-plan first floor. Johnson compiled his famous 'Dictionary of the English Language' (1755)  here.

name: Edith Neville Primary School and Children's Centre
description: Come inside Hayhurst & Co’s intricate, light-filled building, bursting with architectural ideas and extraordinary spatial events to hear how it’s rooted in a coherent educational ethos – and empathy with young children.

name: Estorick Collection of Modern Italian Art
description: The Estorick Collection is housed in a beautiful Georgian building previously known as Northampton Lodge. Today, the museum comprises six galleries over three floors, as well as a library, offices, a café and bookshop.

name: Fitzroy Park Allotments
description: open allotment site, no buildings

name: Fleet Street Heritage Information Project and Sundial
description: This new sundial faces East so gets only morning sun. It is 10 m. square and was opened in 2021, and is publicly accessible 24/7

name: Forma HQ & Peveril Gardens
description: A garden atop a former parking structure at the base of Peveril House. It sits on top of artists studios, also refurbished using minimal interventions by architects Sanchez Benton. Shortlisted for the Open City Stewardship Awards 2021. This project is supported by the Mayor of London.
address: Forma HQ, Peveril Garden Studios, 140 Great Dover St, SE1 4GW

name: Foster + Partners
description: We're excited to open up our London campus as part of Open House Festival. Foster + Partners is a global studio for sustainable architecture, urbanism, engineering and design, founded by Norman Foster in 1967. With offices across the world, the practice works as a single entity that is both ethnically and culturally diverse, with people central to all our endeavours.

name: Four Corners
description: Refurbished extended building, a centre for film and photography. Central courtyard integrated 'hub' allows light and air to filter through. Loft conversion to create studio and work space. Sustainable features include sedum roof.

name: From Forest to Morris: A walk around Walthamstow
description: A walk around historic Walthamstow showing how this unique area grew from a village into a thriving suburb, its social history and the variety of buildings that can be found where Epping Forest meets William Morris.
address: Outside Costa Coffee at Walthamstow Central Station 5 Station Approac

name: Garden Court Chambers
description: Inigo Jones design 1640 at 59/60 LIF, copied  by 57/58  with portico and elliptical staircase added by Soane.  Refurbished by current occupiers, a barristers' chambers. Retains many original features, staircases, fireplaces and mouldings

name: Garden Room
description: Flexible use garden room in a newly established garden.

name: Glenkerry House
description: Glenkerry House is a 14-storey tower block designed by Hungarian architect Ernő Goldfinger. The block is managed by its residents, who collectively form the Glenkerry Co-operative Housing Association.

name: Good Growth in Angel Edmonton
description: Welcoming visitors to Angel Edmonton to explore a number of newly developed places and spaces that are helping steward the area through significant change. Delivered by Enfield Council with support from the Mayor of London.

name: Green House
description: A new exposed CLT-frame house, built on a site once occupied by market garden greenhouses, featuring a planted façade with sliding external screens and a riad-style central atrium, assisting in natural daylighting, ventilation and cooling.

name: Greenwich Millennium Village
description: The most recent chapter of Greenwich Millennium Village’s remarkable 25 year history is told through this audio walking tour, featuring a rich variety of stories from current residents.

name: Guildhall Art Gallery
description:
UPDATED: Open daily 10.30am-4pm. 
Guided tours 12.15pm & 1.15pm on Tuesdays, Thursdays, Fridays, Saturdays & Sundays, see below.
Home of the City of London's art collection, & remains of London's Roman Amphitheatre

name: Gulabi House
description: An extension to an Edwardian terrace house in Tottenham for a young family that marries their cultural backgrounds, inspired by Indian modernism.

name: Haberdashers' Hall
description: Opened by the Queen in 2002 as one of the first new livery halls in the Square Mile for nearly 40 years, this is a brick building with traditional lime mortar and handsome lead roof, standing around a peaceful courtyard.
address: 18 West Smithfield (opposite Barts Hospital by traffic barrier under

name: Hackney Archives - Searchroom Strongroom Tour 16th Sept
description: Join us for a live talk and tour around the searchroom and explore what's in our collections. We will show you how to explore Hackney's past and present.
address: Hackney Archives Dalston Square, CLR James Library, E8 3BQ

name: Haggerston Wharf live-aboard boats
description: A small community of people living aboard an array of traditional and contemporary craft. Open to viewers are two traditional narrowboats and one widebeam. Visit to have your boat toilet related questions answered for once and for all.

name: Haringey's New Council Homes Exhibition & Talks
description: Haringey Council invites you to an exhibition with short talks about our ambitious council homes building programme, including how our new homes help tackle climate change, keep energy bills down, and support our most vulnerable residents.
address: Living Under One Sun, Bowling Green and Pavillion, Down Lane Park

name: Harrow School: Old Schools, Fourth Form Room
description: Best preserved 17C schoolroom in the country. Wainscot panelling, benches, tables and chairs. Original fireplace replaced in 1730, oriel window inserted in 1820. Walls carved with names of every Harrow pupil until 1847.
address: Old Schools, Church Hill, Harrow-on-the-Hill, HA1 3HP

name: Harrow School: Old Speech Room Gallery
description: Purpose built room intended for the teaching of public speaking which figured prominently in the classical curriculum. Converted 1976 by Alan Irvine into modern gallery with mezzanine floor.

name: Hassett
description:
Architects own house in Hackney. 

A very recently completed re-work of a 70's split-level house in Hackney. The house is owned by architect and partner of Archmongers Architects, Johan Hybschmann and his wife Anita Freeman.

name: Havant House 53
description: A victorian mid terrace house with a dark blue exterior and a zany tiled front garden. Full of original features without being dictated by the era, colour continues inside with a yellow rubber floor in the kitchen.

name: Heritage on the High Road (High Street HAZ)
description: Hear about some of the initiatives under way in the Tottenham High Street Heritage Action Zone (High Street HAZ). LB Haringey and the Tottenham Civic Society host a tour uncovering the rich heritage of this bustling, multicultural area.
address: Bruce Grove Public Conveniences, Bruce Grove, N17 6UR

name: Highgate Literary & Scientific Institution
description: Fine stuccoed building overlooking Pond Square, and home to Institution since 1840. Formed from 1790 coach house, stables and yard, with final additions c1880. Guided tours will be available.

name: Highgate School Chapel, Library, Museum
description: Highgate is three schools in one. Founded by Sir Roger Cholmeley, Lord Chief Justice of England, in 1565, Highgate is governed as a single charitable foundation.

name: Highpoint
description: Grade I listed Modernist apartment blocks retaining many original features.

name: Historic & Modern Buildings in the City
description:
On this walk we will see many historic & modern buildings. see different architecture styles having regard to the environment and sustainability, and hear about famous architects, past and present.

Free walks led by City of London Guides

name: Historic Bromley Town Exhibition
description: An Exhibition celebrating the historic character and heritage of Bromley from its origins as a Kentish market town through the Victorian Golden Age to the present time with many buildings in the Arts and Crafts style that can be seen today.
address: Lower Mall, The Glades shopping centre, 64 High Street, Bromley

name: Holy Cross Church, Cromer Street
description: Grade ll listed Oxford Movement Anglican church built 1887-88. Historic England describe the exterior as ‘quirky and aggressive’ but the  interior is ‘very spare and elegant, the proportions subtly adjusted’. Elevated choir and sanctuary.

name: Holy Trinity Church Sloane Square
description: A sumptuous feast of Victorian stained glass & bold sacred sculpture in what Sir John Betjeman called the 'cathedral of the Arts and Crafts movement.' Work by William Morris, Edward Burne-Jones, William Blake- Richmond & Christopher Whall.
address: 146 Sloane Street (just off Sloane Square), SW1X 9BZ

name: Host of Leyton - Pop-Up Gallery - Dan Lee
description:
Host of Leyton is open 12th - 17th Sept to welcome visitors to see the shop & space and view the work of our special Pop-up exhibition by young artist and landscape designer Dan Lee. 
For more info see @thisishost on Instagram.

name: Hounslow Jamia Masjid & Islamic Centre
description: Hounslow Jamia Masjid & Islamic Centre is the largest purpose built Mosque in West London. Serving the needs of the local community and working towards the common good.

name: Housing in Stoke Newington Walking Tour
description: A tour of housing in Stoke Newington from 1714 to 2017. The tour will encompass a range of homes from the outside, and talk about the history of Stoke Newington and the changes it has seen since transforming from a small village to a suburb
address: Clissold Park, Stoke Newington Church St, N16 9HJ

name: Hoxton Hall
description: Hoxton Hall was originally built in 1863 by James Mortimer, in the traditional music hall architecture style, with the intention to combine instruction with amusement.  It is a Grade 2 Listed Plus building and one of 5 Music Hall's left.

name: Ikigai_12 Hickin Street
description: Building tour for a house_Ikigai _12 Hickin Street

name: Imagine Golden Lane at Net Zero - a walking tour
description: A walk from Barbican Underground Station via the Museum of London to Barbican and then to Golden Lane.

name: Institut français du Royaume-Uni
description: 1939 Art Deco Grade II listed building refurbished in 1950, then restructured and modernised in 2014. Contains an authentically classic cinema, private salons and multimedia library.

name: Intersect House
description: Victorian Terraced House in Stoke Newington with a ground floor rear extension and new mansard roof conversion with master bedroom and ensuite by WILLIAM TOZER Associates.

name: Isokon Building (Lawn Road Flats)
description: Grade I listed 1934 residential block of flats in Hampstead, designed by the Canadian modernist architect Wells Coates for clients Jack and Molly Pritchard. English Heritage blue plaque for Bauhaus masters Gropius, Breuer and Moholy-Nagy.

name: JTP Studios, Pennington Street Warehouse
description: Pennington Street Warehouse is a Grade II Listed Warehouse, sensitively adapted in 2019 into a vibrant and creative home for architects & masterplanners, JTP.
address: JTP Studios, Unit 5, The Rum Warehouse, Pennington Street, E1W 2AP

name: Jeffrey's Place
description: Historic 1850s Camden warehouse, recently renovated by Tasou Associates to rationalise internal spaces, open up the building to more natural daylight and create a comfortable office space.

name: Kaymet Factory
description: The operational factory of Kaymet, a maker of trays and trolleys since 1947. A hidden 1950s building with a small yard, originally a printing works. It is brick built, with clear-storey glazing and tubular truss north-light main shed roof.

name: King's College London, The Maughan Library
description: London's first fireproof building, built to house records of the Court of Chancery. Now renovated to house a fine university library.

name: King's College London: Museum of Life Sciences
description: Constructed in 1902 as the Will's Library, part of  Guy's Hospital Medical School. Building of red brick  with additional stonework and partially covered in creeper. Internally are carved oak cabinets and ornate columns.
address: Hodgkin Building, Guy' Campus, King's College London, SE1 1UL

name: Kingston Guildhall and History Centre
description: Built in the Georgian style, the Guildhall brought together Kingston's administrative functions. Purpose-built Magistrates Courts were included in the building, part of which are now home to Kingston History Centre.
address: High Street , Kingston upon Thames, KT1 1EU

name: Kingston Library, Museum and Art Gallery
description: Adjoining Grade II listed Carnegie-funded library, museum and art gallery. Museum holdings range from ceramics to topographical drawings, including the collection left by Eadweard Muybridge, a native of Kingston and photographic pioneer.
address: Wheatfield Way, Kingston upon Thames, KT1 2PS

name: Kitchen in the Woods
description:
Winner of the  Urban Oasis awards of Don't Move Improve 2023! with an extension by A Small Studio architects.

This is an Austin Vernon & Partners 1957 home that sits within the Dulwich Estate.

name: La Sainte Union Catholic School
description: Founded in 1861 by a group of French nuns, La Sainte Union has a rich history. See the original Georgian site, chapel and its 141-year-old organ, plus modern stained glass windows by Patrick Pollen, LSU’s own orchard and the 60s extension.

name: Lakeside Centre
description: Iconic brutalist building in the heart of Thamesmead, renovation led by Bow Arts Trust in partnership with Peabody, supported by the Mayor’s London Regeneration Fund (LEAP). The centre has opened as a cultural hub for Thamesmead.
address: Southmere Lake Complex, 2 Bazalgette Way (formerly Belvedere Road)

name: Lancaster House
description: Commissioned in 1825 by the Duke of York and named York House.  In 1829 the lease was purchased by the first Duke of Sutherland.  In 1913, Lord Leverhulme, bought the lease for the nation and Stafford House became Lancaster House.

name: Lansbury Lawrence Primary School
description: Lansbury Lawrence (formally Susan Lawrence and Elizabeth Lansbury) opened in the 1951 Festival of Britain as a showpiece of the Live Architecture exhibition in the Lansbury Estate. An interesting mid-century design with original features.

name: Lesnes Abbey Tour
description: Archaeologist Anthony Thomas leads a tour on the history of Lesnes Abbey.
address: Lesnes Abbey Lodge,  Abbey Road, SE2 0QJ

name: Lewisham Arthouse
description: Lewisham Arthouse (LAH) is a not-for-profit artist-led co-operative, based in the formerly Deptford Central Library, Grade II listed, 1910 -1914, Designed by A. Brumwell Thomas (1868 -1948)

name: Lexi Cinema
description: A contemporary extension to the Lexi Cinema, providing a 2nd screen. The building is a composition of brick and stainless steel; a nod to the parapets of surrounding terraces and reflecting the ever-changing sky above.

name: Leyton House
description: Leyton House is a new build house that has been designed to maximise the potential of its urban infill setting.

name: Little Mouse Cheese Shop
description: Visit Little Mouse, an Edwardian shop in South Norwood with original wooden frontage and fascia that is now an artisan cheesemonger.

name: London Metropolitan Archives
description: LMA's older building was built in the late 1930s for the Temple Press and has many original features.   Purpose built extension in early 1990s for archival storage. Public rooms remodelled by Bisset Adams in 2000s.

name: London Open Form Pavilion of Air
description: A floating roof of sound, GPS-triggered & accessed by headphones & Echoes app to playfully reframe public space as an essential community engagement. One of 15 in an international series drawing on Oskar & Zofia Hansen’s Open Form concept.

name: London's Roman Amphitheatre
description:
UPDATED: Open daily 10.30am-4pm Closed Mon 19 September.
Combined guided tours of Amphitheatre and Guildhall Art Gallery at 12.15pm & 1.15pm on Tuesdays, Thursdays, Fridays, Saturdays & Sundays.
The capital’s only known Roman Amphitheatre
address: London’s Roman Amphitheatre at Guildhall Art Gallery, Guildhall Yard

name: Manor House Gardens Ice House
description: Grade II listed ice well and underground chambers (1770) in Manor House Gardens park, which provided ice for nearby Manor House. Cited in 2002 Civic Trust Awards.

name: Mansion House
description: The official residence of the Lord Mayor of the City of London, retaining its 18C character, with superb plasterwork and wood carving.

name: Markfield Beam Engine and House
description: A masterpiece of Victorian engineering, Markfield Beam Engine provided a vital public health facility from 1855-1964.
address: Markfield Park, Markfield Road, South Tottenham, N15 4RB

name: Marx Memorial Library & Workers' School
description: Grade II listed, built as a Welsh Charity School in 1738. A library with a focus on Marxism and Socialism since 1933. Lenin worked here 1902-03 and his office is preserved. Fresco by Jack Hastings in 1st floor. Late 15C tunnels.

name: Mission Kitchen
description: Mission Kitchen is a shared workspace for London's independent food businesses. It supports a community of more than 100 food and drink entrepreneurs.  This project is supported by the Mayor of London.
address: Mission Kitchen, New Covent Garden Market, SW8 5EL

name: Modern Architecture in Blackheath walk
description: Architect Ana Sutherland will lead a guided tour of the Cator Estate, covering Eric Lyons' Span estates and unique modernist homes designed by architects Patrick Gwynne, Peter Moro and Walter Greaves.

name: Moorings Social Club
description:
Newly refurbished former social club, which is now a multi-use community space in the heart of Satge 3 Thamesmead - The Moorings 
Open Access and Tours running all day

name: Mother X Artists and Makers Open Studios
description: Mother X is a diverse group of artists, makers & creators that have inhabited a former Victorian chocolate factory in Hackney Wick for 15+ years. Come visit this unique building & see it's people & their work during the Open House Festival.
address: Floor D, Unit 9 Queen's Yard, Hackney Wick, E9 5EN

name: Museum of London Docklands
description: Grade I listed, late Georgian sugar warehouse now housing the Museum of London Docklands. Sensitively restored, the new multimedia displays coexist with the massive timber and brick structures of the original building.
address: No. 1 Warehouse, West India Quay (off Hertsmere Road), E14 4AL

name: Museum of the Order of St John
description: St John's Gate in Clerkenwell dates from 1504 and was built for the Knights Hospitaller. 19th and early 20th century additions by Richard Norman Shaw and John Oldrid Scott. Grade I listed. Home to the Museum of the Order of St John.
address: St John's Gate, St John's Lane, Clerkenwell, EC1M 4DA

name: Muswell Hill Baptist Church
description: A notable example of George Baines' work from the heyday of London free church buildings. It combines Baptist simplicity with Edwardian decor and spaciousness and is broadly unaltered.  It was built to complement the surrounding townscape.
address: Muswell Hill Baptist Church, Dukes Avenue, N10 2PT

name: NOW Gallery : Design District
description: The NOW Gallery is an art space - contained within two curved glass pavilions linked by a patinated brass-edged canopy - which defines the southern edge of Peninsula Square and acts as a gateway to the south, the cable car and Central Park.
address: The Gateway Pavilions, Peninsula Square, Greenwich Peninsula

name: National Audit Office
description: A prestigious Grade II listed building. Opened in 1939 by Imperial Airways and subsequently used by BOAC and then British Airways. The building has been the home of the National Audit Office since 1986 and was refurbished in 2009.

name: National Maritime Museum
description: We are aiming to do four free guided tours that are normally paid with which we can offer max up to 25 people on each. We will also have drop in talks run by the Visitor and Sales team on specific subjects for people to drop into.

name: National Portrait Gallery Architecture Highlights Tours
description: Discover the architecture of the National Portrait Gallery, designed in 1896 by Ewan Christian and now transformed by Jamie Fobert Architects. Please meet at the Ross Street Entrance. Drop-in 9, 10, 16 & 17 September specific times listed below.
address: National Portrait Gallery, St Martin's Place, WC2H 0HE

name: North London Buddhist Centre
description: The North London Buddhist Centre has been described as an 'oasis along the Holloway road'. It just celebrated its 20th anniversary in its current premises built in 1980 with some elements of Georgian style. The building houses two shrine rooms, a café area and  bodywork studio.
address: North London Buddhist Centre, 72 Holloway Road, N7 8GJ

name: Oak Room, New River Head
description: Formerly boardroom of the 17C water house, the Oak Room is a fine late Renaissance room demonstrating the New River Company's wealth. Booking link: https://bit.ly/OakRooms
address: New River Head, , 173 Rosebery Avenue, EC1R 4UL

name: Old Royal Naval College - King William Court
description: Wren-designed building completed under the direction of Hawksmoor and Vanbrugh, 1698-1712. Original wood panelling, refurbished by Dannatt Johnson in 2001 for University of Greenwich.
address: King William Court, 30 Park Row, SE10 9NN

name: Old Royal Naval College - Queen Anne Court
description: Wren and Hawksmoor building, completed 1749 when Thomas Ripley built the pavilions facing the river. Highlights include council boardroom, grand staircase and restored Portland stonework. Refurbished in 2000 for University of Greenwich.
address: Queen Anne Court , 30 Park Row, SE10 9NN

name: Old Royal Naval College - Queen Mary Court
description: Last major building on the site (1751). Original layout, timber panelling, barrel vaulting and Portland stone. Refurbished in 2000 by Dannatt Johnson for University of Greenwich.
address: Queen Mary Court, 30 Park Row, SE10 9NN

name: Olden Community Garden
description: Olden Community Garden - a hidden 2.5 acre green oasis along a railway embankment in Islington. Sit beside the lawn; listen to birdsong; follow trails into the woodland and orchard; discover vegetable patches. Help plant lavender hedge.

name: Outdoor exhibition celebrating the 900th anniversary of St Bartholomew’s Hospital - Life and death in the archives, 1123-2023
description: Life and death in the archives, 1123-2023, is a unique exhibition detailing St Bartholomew’s Hospital's history and people, using photography, art and history from our archives and collections
address: St Bartholomew's Hospital, West Smithfield, EC1A 7BE

name: Paxton Locher House
description: A unique modern courtyard house making brilliant use of a restricted site. A retractable glass roof gives wonderful natural light and opens the house to the sky in dry weather.

name: People's Museum Somers Town
description:
A great little museum set in the Grade 2 listed Ossulston Estate - a prime example of pre-war Social housing - based on Karl Marz Hof in Vienna.
Open Wednesdays to Saturdays throughout Festival 
Sunday 11th Event

name: Peter Cushing House
description: 1920s Art Deco house, formerly the home of Peter Cushing OBE. English Heritage Blue Plaque.

name: Pollard Thomas Edwards - Diespeker Wharf
description: Conversion of a canalside Victorian warehouse, formerly a terrazzo factory, into spacious offices, garden and glazed extension with one of the best waterside views in London. Refurbished, 2022.

name: Poroban studio
description: Poroban is a multi-disciplinary design studio, based off Old Kent Road, specialising in low carbon building design. We are offering free design surgeries throughout September and are hosting an open day on Saturday 9th Sept.

name: Present & Correct Stationers
description: Architecture for London designed and built a new home for stationers Present & Correct in a heritage retail unit. In a nod to the neighbouring British Museum, cabinets as 'wunderkammer' display the stationery as objects of desire.

name: Purley Way to Wandle Park
description: This tour will give an insight into the many different eras and building styles represented on one of Croydon's busiest streets- from Victorian industry, the World Wars, Brutalism and even a ghost swimming pool.
address: Purley War Memorial Hospital, 856 Brighton Road, Purley, Croydon

name: Pushkin House
description: The independent cultural centre Pushkin House will contribute to this year's Open House Festival through a programme of events and community initiatives at its Grade-II listed building in Bloomsbury Square.

name: Quaker Meeting House - Wandsworth
description: Grade II listed, this is the oldest Quaker meeting house in London. Built in 1778, it has original panelling & a minister's gallery. See flagstones from the earlier 1674 buildings. Also a secluded burial ground & garden. Free refreshments.

name: Queer City: LGBTQ + stories and spaces in Soho
description: This alternative queer walking tour will explore queer places in London’s pleasure district of Soho and the surrounding parts of Westminster, focusing on lesbian, bisexual and trans stories through an intersectional lens.
address: Criterion Theatre opposite Eros, 218-223 Piccadilly, W1J 9HR

name: Quentin Blake Centre for Illustration - New River Head
description:
An industrial heritage site that was the hub of one of London’s first major pieces of urban infrastructure.
Its 18th and 19th century buildings will be restored by Tim Ronalds Architects to create the Quentin Blake Centre for Illustration.
address: Quentin Blake Centre for Illustration, Rear of 28 Amwell Street

name: RC Church of St Mellitus
description: A grand neo-classical building of 1871 with impressive interior, built as New Court Congregational Chapel. Home to a Hunter pipe organ, installed as a WW1 memorial and recently restored with National Lottery Heritage Fund support.
address: St Mellitus RC Church, Tollington Park, N4 3AG

name: RSHP at The Leadenhall Building
description: The award-winning Leadenhall Building was designed by international architects RSHP in 2014. L14 became the practice's headquarters in 2015. The Studio is a completely open plan office, reflecting the democratic beliefs of the practice.

name: Rear and basement extension of a riverside house
description: An opportunity to experience a private home situated on the bankside of River Thames. A contextual intervention by VATRAA, restoring and extending a Victorian house with an atmospheric feel inspired by the homeowner's personality.

name: Red Door Studios: Family workshop, Exhibition featuring Ferha Farooqui's painting and more
description: This is an artist-run, community-focused space, that offers affordable studios since 2011. Built around 1893 and adjacent to Almshouses. Also, used as a bakery and later became laboratory glassware in the late 1950s.
address: Rear of 120 High Street South, E6 3RW

name: Reform Club
description: Built as a Whig gentleman's club and inspired by Italian Renaissance palaces. Lobby leads to an enclosed colonnaded courtyard with complementary glazed roof and tessellated floor. Tunnelled staircase leads to upper floor.

name: Rigpa Tibetan Buddhist Meditation Centre
description: Open day would include pop -up tearoom with artisan teas, handmade cakes and savouries, bookshop and library . Regular guided tours, guided meditation sessions, family sessions,  introductory Buddhist talks, Buddhist film screening

name: River Walk
description: London could never have existed without the Thames. For 2000 yrs it has brought power, prestige pageantry and the plague to this great city. Hear about the role of London Bridge, mud-larking, Billingsgate, historic wharves and river tales.

name: Roca London Gallery
description: Designed by the world renowned Zaha Hadid Architects, Roca London Gallery is a unique space where water acts as the architectural theme. Guests can also visit 'Small Spaces in the City: Rethinking Inside the Box', a major exhibition exploring the challenges and innovative solutions for small live-and-work spaces in the city.

name: Royal College of Nursing
description: A cleverly integrated mixture of architectural styles and periods, incorporating a late 1720s house (later home to Herbert Henry Asquith) and the purpose-built College of Nursing (1926). Access to main building via guided tour only.

name: Royal Courts of Justice
description: Street's masterpiece and one of Victorian London's great public buildings. 13C Gothic given a Victorian interpretation.

name: Royal Hospital Chelsea, Home of the Chelsea Pensioners
description:
Numbered amongst the UK's architectural glories and boasting 66 acres of beautiful grounds, the Royal Hospital Chelsea has been home to the iconic Army veteran community fondly known as the 'Chelsea Pensioners' since its foundation in 1692. 
The Great Hall and Chapel will not be accessible from 12.00-14.00 on Saturday 16th September due to an internal event. The remainder of the site will be open during this time. 

Visitors should note that filming will be taking place during the afternoon of Sunday 17th September. If you would like to be excluded from any filming, please let our staff and volunteers know on arrival at the site.

name: Royal Pharmaceutical Society Museum
description:
Join us for a free guided tour of the RPS Museum and Library and find out what crocodiles have to do with pharmacy!
Over 180 years old, the RPS Museum and Library is a hidden gem in East London, full of the weird and wonderful world of pharmacy history.
Find out how best to use bear’s grease and explore a collection of poisons even Agatha Christie would swoon at!

Scroll down to find out more

name: Royal School of Needlework
description: Baroque palace built for King William III and Mary II. The original Tudor towers and chimneys were replaced by grand and elegant exteriors that dominate the buildings today.
address: RSN Shop, East Front Gardens, Hampton Court Palace, KT8 9AU

name: Royal Small Arms Factory
description: Grade II listed arms factory closed to public for 170 years. Museum and clocktower open for tours.
address: RSA Island Centre, 49 Island Centre Way

name: Rufford Mews Apartment
description: The interior of this property has been designed by Mike McMahon and the majority of the furniture and cabinetry have been made by Mike & Jewlsy over the course of a number of years including lighting, chairs, sofas, beds etc.

name: Schindel Studio
description: Schindel studio is a shingle clad, purpose built, sustainable artist's studio in Leytonstone, East London, for the landscape painter Amelia Humber.

name: Sheppard Robson 77 Parkway
description: Nestled off a busy street in Camden, the former industrial building has been home to architectural firm Sheppard Robson for over 40 years. A series of additions have allowed more amenity, social spaces, and diversity in work settings.

name: Slavery and the City
description: We will explore sites and institutions with direct links to the history of slavery and hear why the apologies were made in 2020, whilst wandering within the story packed streets and alleyways of the Square Mile.

name: South Norwood Library
description: The purpose-built library is a fine example of brutalist architecture. Built by Hugh Lea, Borough Architect for Croydon, in 1968 the main volume shows miesian influence with an abundance of natural light, interrupted by a concrete cuboid.

name: Southwark Integrated Waste Management Facility
address: 43 Devon Street, (off Old Kent Road), SE15 1AL

name: St Andrew's Kingsbury (new church)
description: Meticulous 1930s rebuilding (complete with original furnishings) of an 1840s Marylebone church. Grade I listed. Contains works by Pugin, Burges, Street, Pearson and Butterfield.
address: junction of Church Lane/Tudor Gardens/ Old Church Lane, Kingsbury

name: St Anne's Church, Limehouse
description: St Anne's Limehouse has been described as 'the finest parish church in England.' Designed by Nicholas Hawksmoor, it is Grade I listed and one of the Major Churches in the Church of England. It is home to a thriving Christian congregation.

name: St Augustine of Canterbury
description: Victorian/Arts and Crafts church completed in 20C. Imposing west front by J Harold Gibbons with statuary by Dorothy Rope. Lady chapel by Henry Wilson. Stained glass by Margaret Aldridge Rope. Fine Hunter organ plus case.
address: Corner Archway Road & Langdon Park Road, N6 5BH

name: St Augustine's Tower
description: Grade I listed, remaining tower of medieval parish church, with working late 16C clock. New exhibition of Hackney's history. Extensive views from roof. (Organised by Hackney Historic Buildings Trust).

name: St Bonifatius RC German Church
description: Centre of German religious and cultural life for more than 200 years. Impressive 20th century church building with contributions from various German artists. Exhibition of German émigré artist Hans Feibusch „Five Stories from the Old Testament“ (courtesy of Ben Uri Gallery). Demonstration of the organ by resident organist Paul Dichtl.

name: St John on Bethnal Green
description: This grade one listed Sir John Soane church sits in the heart of the Bethnal Green in East London. Despite a fire in 1870, some original features remain. Visitors will have access to the church,  belfry, galleries and crypt.
address: St John on Bethnal Green, 200 Cambridge Heath Road, E2 9PA

name: St John the Divine
description: St John’s has a wide nave approached via a narthex formed under the gallery running the width of the west end.  East of the nave is a chancel flanked to the south by the Lady Chapel and to the north by the organ chamber with loft over.

name: St Jude on the Hill
description: Eccentric Edwardian church, Grade I listed. Described by Simon Jenkins as 'one of Lutyens' most distinctive creations'. Extensive 20C wall-paintings by Walter Starmer, memorial to horses of WWI. Local archives display.

name: St Lawrence Church, Morden
description: Grade I listed Norman brick-built church consisting of a nave and chancel. Tower at the west end. Gothic-style stone windows from the old church inserted into the present 1636 structure. Rare 17th Century glass was restored in 2020.

name: St Martin-in-the-Fields
description: One of Britain's finest churches, built in the Italian Baroque tradition and beautifully restored in 2008. Sustainable features include new heating and management systems and lightwell. RIBA Award Winner 2009. Civic Trust Award Winner 2010.

name: St Mary Magdalene
description: A historic living parish church, progressively shaped from the Tudor to the Edwardian period. St Mary's has recently undergone a major refurbishment and the newly restored windows recapture the original airiness of the C18 nave.

name: St Mary Magdalene Church
description: Fine Victorian Gothic church with impressive windows and painted chancel. Paintings by Buckeridge and Westlake 1897. Restoration of chancel paintings was to celebrate the Diamond Jubilee of Queen Elizabeth II. (2012)

name: St Mary Magdalene Church & Nature Reserve
description: Grade I listed 12C church, with London's largest churchyard and one of the best-preserved Norman archways in the country, as well as other interesting features, including an anchorite's cell and 750-year-old wall paintings.
address: St Mary Magdalene Church, East Ham, High Street South/ Norman Road

name: St Mary The Virgin Wanstead
description: One of the finest examples of Georgian architecture. It has been hardly altered since built. The church is a rectangular building of Portland stone, with a projecting chancel. Two external walls were restored in 2019. Grade I listed
address: St Mary The Virgin Church , Overton Drive, E11 2LW

name: St Mary's Church Bromley
description:
A plain Victorian Church set in a wooded Churchyard, with a vibrant and striking set of Murals around the altar and the Choir. 
Has indoor toilet facilities. 
A good quality well used organ in good condition, and an excellent accoustic
address: St Mary's Church, College Road, Bromley, BR1 3QG

name: St Mary's Convent
description:
Convent in 18C Grade II listed house, c1764-1792, with original features including fine decorative plasterwork. Various additions including west wing (1913-15), and harmonious care home facilities and chapel by PRP Architects (1998-2001).
Apologies to visitors turned away last year. Please book for this year.

name: St Matthew's Church
description:
St Matthews is Grade II listed, built 1883-4 and designed by the architect Alfred Jowers. 
It features a WW1 memorial screen designed by Reginald Hallward and stained glass some believed to be by Edward Frampton
address: St Matthews church, North Common Road, W5 2QA

name: St Michael and All Angels Church
description: James Maltby Bignall (1827-1885) worked in the practice of Sir George Gilbert Scott, the architect of St Pancras Station. The style of St Michael's is late Gothic Revival, in its size and height reminiscent of Northern European churches.

name: St Nicholas Church, Chislehurst
description: Medieval Parish Church, 15C, enlarged & rebuilt in 19C. Shingle spire 1857, by Wollaston. Chancel by Ferrey, lengthened with East wall by Bodley & Garner. Scadbury Chapel (Walsingham tombs), with rood screen. Clock by Dent, 1858.

name: St Pancras Chambers and Clock Tower
description: Former Midland Grand Hotel, now St Pancras Renaissance Hotel and Chambers apartments. Includes hotel lobby and clock tower.
address: The Forecourt, St Pancras Station, Euston Road, NW1 2AR

name: St Patrick's Church
description: Built thanks to a generous gift from local benefactress, Mrs Lavinia Keene, St Patrick's was consecrated in July 1940 and is unusual in style. The concrete and brick interior contrasts with the dramatic, colourful reredos. Grade II listed.

name: St Paul's Bow Common
description: Described as 'the most significant church built after the WWII in Britain' - Brutalist, inclusive and influential signpost for future church design.
address: Corner of Burdett Road/ St Paul's Way, E3 4AR

name: St Paul's Cathedral - Triforium Tour
description: Guided tours of the Triforium space to see: items from the cathedral collections including Christopher Wren’s magnificent ‘Great Model’ made in 1673; the Geometrical Staircase and the stunning view from the West Gallery.
address: St Paul's Cathedral, St Paul's Churchyard, EC4M 8AD

name: St Paul's, Newington
description: Modern architecture church with large copper and lead roof and concrete, brick and stained glass external structure. Marble, wood and plaster interior and artwork by Sculptor Freda Pinto and Gerald Holtom.

name: St Peter & St Paul Harlington
description: Grade I listed church dating from 1086, representing the architectural styles of many centuries, including Norman font and carved cats heads around Norman south doorway arch, Easter sepulchre and ancient yew tree in churchyard.
address: St Peter's Way, High Street, Harlington, UB3 5AB

name: St Peter-in-the-Forest Church & Community Centre
description: An 'Italian Romanesque' church set in Epping Forest, St Peter's was founded in 1840 and extended in 1887. The building underwent a major reordering throughout 2020 to save it from subsidence and create new community facilities.

name: St. Margaret's House
description: St.Margaret's has delivered community activity on Old Ford Road since the start of the 20th century.
address: St Margaret’s House, 21 Old Ford Road, E2 9PL

name: St. Mary's Church, Walthamstow Village
description: Grade II* listed church dating from 12C with Medieval, Tudor, Georgian & Victorian features. 16C Tower. Church refurbishment and new extension in progress in 2022. Over 1300 monuments with four Grade II listed tombs in churchyard.
address: Church End (top of Church Hill), Walthamstow, E17 9RJ

name: Stoke Newington Library Open Studios
description: Stoke Newington Library houses 9 artist studios that most of the visiting public are unaware of. The artists are holding an Open Studio day on Saturday 16 September, 10.30am –5pm. The studios are not wheelchair accessible.

name: StreetGym® Urban Adventure
description: StreetGym® is a one hour, mind/body urban physical adventure where we jog from workstation to workstation.  A workstation is an item of street furniture, gradient or architectural feature where we perform bodyweight based exercises.
address: Back End of the Millennium Bridge (Tate Modern side), Southwark

name: Surbiton Queen of the Suburbs
description:
Join us for an interesting and informative walk around Surbiton with our experienced guide. Find out why Surbiton was called the Queen of the suburbs and plenty more. 

Visit our website: https://www.kingstontourguides.org.uk/

name: Swakeleys Estate
description: A most important house in Ickenham an outstanding example of Jacobean architecture built in the 1630s. Red brick construction laid in English bond on an H plan. Great Hall includes the 1655 Harrington Screen, 18C marble fireplace panelling.
address: Swakeleys Road, Ickenham (access from Milton Road) , UB10 8LD

name: Swiss Cottage Library
description: Grade II listed building by renowned Modernist which has been refurbished and remodelled whilst protecting the building's landmark status.

name: Table Top Museums at the Art Workers' Guild
description: 1713 terraced house with 1914 hall at rear. Notable renovated Arts and Crafts interior. Newly refurbished glass vaulted courtyard. Portraits of Guild Masters since 1884.

name: Temple Bar
description: Temple Bar is a 350 year old gateway to the City of London, designed by Sir Christopher Wren. It formerly stood in Fleet Street, and was the last surviving gateway to the City of London.
address: First Floor, Paternoster Lodge, 2 Paternoster Square, EC4M 7DX

name: Thames River Police
description: A unique ex-carpenters' workshop (1910), contained within a working police station. The workshop space now displays a history of Thames River Police.

name: The Barbican & The City Gardens
description: Built on the site destroyed by The Blitz during the World War II, The Barbican Estate is a fascinating area and an icon of Brutalist architecture. Architects were Chamberlain, Powell and Bon,  We  will also visit several amazing gardens.

name: The Blue Market - Made in Bermondsey
description: Following three years of research and development, the ‘Made in Bermondsey’ people powered regeneration project was created and driven by passionate local community partners who truly care about the place where they live or their business. This project is supported by the Mayor of London.
address: Big Local Works, 4 Market Place, SE16 3UQ

name: The Building Crafts College, Kennard Road, Stratford
description: Tour of our facilities

name: The Church of St Mary's and new community centre
description: The Church was built in 1874 by R.J Withers. The adjoining building was remodeled by Goodhart Rendell in the 1920s Arts and Crafts style. The Pineapple Project for community use, by Matthew Lloyd Architects, was completed this year.
address: The Church of St Mary's Bourne Street, Westminster, SW1W 8JJ

name: The City Churches: The Priory Church of St Bartholomew the Great
description: The oldest surviving church in the City of London founded in 1123. Originally part of an Augustinian Priory the church survived the Great Fire and the Blitz.

name: The Earls Court Development Company
description: Learn about our plans to transform this 40-acre site into a largely car free mixed use development that aims to go beyond net zero and bring the wonder back to Earls Court
address: Earls Court Project Rooms, 16-18 Empress Place, SW6 1TT

name: The Gilbert & George Centre
description: The Gilbert & George Centre was originally established as a registered charity by the artist in 2009 with the objective to advance the education of the public in the arts, and generally to advance the arts, architecture, heritage and culture for the benefit of the public.

name: The Great Fire of London
description:
In 1666, the conflagration devastated most of the City, thousands of houses, many churches and St Paul's Cathedral destroyed. Christopher Wren played a major role in rebuilding the City. 
Free walks led by City of London Guides

name: The Hospital Chapel of St Mary & St Thomas
description: Founded c1145 by the Abbess of Barking as a hospice for thirteen old and infirm men, the present building is 12C and 19C. Grade II* listed with many interesting monuments, including Burne-Jones windows.

name: The Makers Building and Avanti Architects’ offices
description: Join us on September 16th for guided tours of the award-winning innovative Makers Building in Hackney. Explore the school, residential spaces, and new square. Refreshments and project materials available at Avanti Architect's office nearby.
address: The Makers Building, 1 Jasper Walk, N1 7TW

name: The Old Town Hall, Richmond
description: Red brick and Bath stone grand 'Elizabethan Renaissance' style building altered by war, political changes and reflecting Richmond's history.
address: Old Town Hall, Whittaker Avenue, Richmond, TW9 1TP

name: The Paper Garden
description: This summer Jan Kattein Architects complete one of the most ambitious circular economy buildings attempted in the UK in decades. The 300m2 educational building  in Canada Water forms part of the Paper Garden, for charity Global Generation.

name: The Queen's House
description: Home to an internationally renowned art collection, Inigo Jones’ architectural masterpiece is the first Classical building in the UK. Home to the largest collection of Maritime art and currently hosting an exhibition on the Van de Velde's.

name: The Rowe
description: The re-adaptation and extension of the former Cass School of Art and Architecture provides over 150,000 square feet of office space.

name: The Royal Society
description: A spectacular Grade I listed building designed by famed architect John Nash. Built in 1831, these former townhouses have undergone refurbishments throughout their history. The building is now home to the UK's national science academy.
address: The Royal Society, 6-9 Carlton House Terrace, SW1Y 5AG

name: The Secret Garden Flat
description: A self-built bedroom extension and studio situated behind a shop in a Victorian terrace that shifts the emphasis of living away from a busy main road towards its garden. It recently won ‘Home of the Year’ at the Don’t Move Improve! Awards.

name: The Soho Poly
description: From 1972 to 1990, the Soho Poly was London’s leading Fringe theatre venue - dedicated to widening access to the arts giving voice to underrepresented playwrights and actors, particularly women and those from BAME and LGBTQ+ communities.
address: University of Westminster, 16 Riding House St, W1W 7DT

name: The Tin Tabernacle / Cambridge Hall
description:
Built 1863 - a large corrugated iron chapel. Inside was transformed after the last war into a battleship by local sailors for Sea Cadets. 
It has decks, portholes a Bofors Gun and alter from the set of the 1964 film Becket.

name: The Wash Houses
description: RIBA award-winning building.  Part listed frontage with purpose built archive and exhibition building added to the rear in 2002. The building now houses the University's Special Collections & Archives

name: Theatre Royal Stratford East
description: Grade II* listed. Built as a playhouse and entertaining audiences for over 100 years. An original Victorian auditorium with beautiful Frank Matcham interior with state-of the-art backstage and front of house facilities.

name: Timothy Hatton Architects – The Foundry
description: Tucked behind a busy road in W12, this former foundry is a multi-level development featuring an architects’ studio with courtyards and spaces for exhibitions and musical performances. The  building's 15m brick chimney is a local landmark.

name: Tour the Square Root Factory
address: Unit D11, Leyton Industrial Village, Argall Avenue, E10 7QP

name: Tours of All Saints (EPR Architects), Austral Street
description: Join EPR Architects for tours of our new net zero carbon in operation London studio, All Saints. Led by the project architects, we will delve into the rich history and stories behind the building, and what inspired our innovative design.
address: EPR Architects, All Saints, Austral Street, SE11 4SJ

name: Tower Hamlets Town Hall
description: Tower Hamlets Town Hall, the new headquarters for the London Borough of Tower Hamlets Council, encompasses the restoration of the Grade II listed former Royal London Hospital building, and the addition of a new build extension.

name: Town of Tomorrow: Thamesmead Through Film Walking Tour
